<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-22T17:04:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-22T17:04:00-05:00" n="996" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d996">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3348.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at
                                    Chihuahua</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Chihuahua</hi> (<hi rend="italic">via El Paso,
                                        Tex.</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-22T15:00:00-07:04">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 22, 1912—3 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>There are press reports of prohibition entry foodstuffs through Paso del
                            Norte, which will cause much bitterness toward Americans. In this event
                            mines can not continue beyond two weeks at any rate, and so think better
                            close at once and Americans withdraw. It seems to me that such action
                            coupled with strict enforcement the President’s proclamation will
                            effectively stifle the revolution. Unless <pb facs="0873" n="757" xml:id="pg_757"/> otherwise instructed will counsel withdrawal
                            Americans and closing mines immediately upon notice of the President’s
                            approval of action prohibiting exportation food through Paso del
                            Norte.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Letcher.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>